To demonstrate time series analysis and forecasting, we will use a dataset of clothing sales, available publicly as part of collection of retail data at kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/census/advance-retail-sales-time-series-collection.

In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 300
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8,5)

register_matplotlib_converters()

The usual suspects packages are loaded, including some specific statsmodels functions. The only one you might be unfamiliar with is pmdarima - a Python implementation of R's venerable auto.arima.

The last two lines are requested by matplotlib - it'll work without them but give a warning.

Load our data:

Let's start with a basic test. The (augmented) Dickey-Fuller test tells us whether our data is stationary. The Null is that it's non-stationary

In [3]:
result = adfuller(data.value)
print(f"ADF Stat = {result[0]}")
print(f"p-value = {result[1]}")

ADF Stat = -0.12197098575045945
p-value = 0.9472056885348812

That's pretty emphatic; our data appears non-stationary.

We can explore the autocorrelattion - the extent to which the value at point x is dependent on the values before x

In [6]:
plot_acf(data, lags=48)
plt.show()

This shows clearly that the data has a yearly seasonality. The value of $x_{i}$ is shown to be highly correlated with the value of $x_{-12}$, $x_{-24}$ etc.

We can also check the partial autocorrelation; the correlation at lag $t$ after correlations for lags less than $t$ have been removed.

In [7]:
plot_pacf(data, lags=48)
plt.show()

/home/david/.local/share/virtualenvs/sandp-7vUs6RRU/lib/python3.6/site-packages/statsmodels/regression/linear_model.py:1283: RuntimeWarning: invalid value encountered in sqrt
  return rho, np.sqrt(sigmasq)

At first glance the correaltion at 15 months appears significant. And perhaps it is, but notice the y-axis. Even this outlying point is still less than a 0.3 correlation and thus not convincing evidence of a hidden pattern.

There are no obviius additional patterns evident here, so we conclude that the 12-month seasonality of the data is the most significant aspect for any model to capture.

By differencing - displaying the difference between consecutive observations - we can often find a stationary aspect to non-stationary data. This is useful for some calulations and analysis.

In this case, we expect our data to be seasonal, with at least a peak around Xmas time.

We will use both standard and seasonal differencing, to demonstrate how they differ:

In [8]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10,5), dpi=300, sharex=True)

axes[0].plot(data[:], label="Original Series")
axes[0].plot(data[:].diff(1), label="Standard Differencing")
axes[0].set_title("Standard Differencing")
axes[0].legend(loc="upper left", fontsize=10)

axes[1].plot(data[:], label="Original Series")
axes[1].plot(data[:].diff(12), label="Seasonal Differencing", color="green")
axes[1].set_title("Seasonal Differencing")
plt.legend(loc="upper left", fontsize=10)
plt.suptitle("Clothing Sales", fontsize=16)
plt.show()

Clearly normal differencing is inadequate, it completely fails to account for the seasonality. Seasonal differencing doesn't completely model our data, but it gets a lot closer to stationary.

We want to identify the seasonal component and the general trend. For this we use decomposition, specifically the seasonal_decomposition function from statsmodels. In the previous chart, the seasonal differencing shows a stable variance; for this reason we will use an additive model of seasonality in our decomposition. THe alternative - if the seasonal difference was itself changing - we'd use a multiplicative model.

In [10]:
decomp = seasonal_decompose(data, model="additive", freq=12)
decomp.plot()
plt.show()

We can observe a stable upward trend, broken only by the financial crisis 0f 2008. A very consistent seasonality accounts for nearly 15k variation in sales, meaning the residuals - the portion of the data unaccounted for by either trend or seasonality - make up only a maximum of about 4k variation.

For forecasting we will create an ARIMA model (SARIMA in fact, due to the seasonality).

We can use the pmdarima package to automate the process of finding the optimal values of p, d and q. This could take a few minutes to run:

In [11]:
smodel = pm.auto_arima(data, start_p=1, start_q=1, test="adf", max_p=3, max_q=3, m=12, start_P=0, seasonal=True,
                       d=None, D=1, trace=True, error_action="ignore", suppress_warnings=True, stepwise=True)

That might look overwhelming, but we don't need to concern ourselves with it. pmdarima has identified the optimal orders for the model.

We can then use that model to predict sales for the next 36 months:

In [12]:
n_periods = 36
fitted, confint = smodel.predict(n_periods=n_periods, return_conf_int=True)
index_of_fc = pd.date_range(data.index[-1], periods=n_periods, freq="MS")

fitted_series = pd.Series(fitted, index=index_of_fc)
lower_series = pd.Series(confint[:,0], index=index_of_fc)
upper_series = pd.Series(confint[:,1], index=index_of_fc)

plt.plot(data)
plt.plot(fitted_series, color="darkblue")
plt.fill_between(lower_series.index, lower_series, upper_series, color="k", alpha=0.15)

plt.title("Sarima forecast of clothing sales")
plt.show()

The SARIMA model predicts a slight downturn in sales, but the confidence interval enough that a continued increasing trend would not be surprising. This might be useful for planning long-term stock acquisition, for example.
